<TEXT>
japan has become the most earthquakeconscious 
nation in the world since the earth shook in 1923 and destroyed 
tokyo but the next great quake probably will be a human and 
economic disaster despite all precautions 
tokyo had 2 million people when the earthqake struck now 12 
million people live in the city and the nation is a pillar of 
finance with worlds richest stock exchange and the most money 
flowing out to international capital markets 
predictions about the next great earthquake its due about 
1993 if calculations of a 70year cycle are correct include 
casualties in tens of thousands and a setback for the world as 
japanese money stays home to rebuild 
a lot is being done to lessen the effect more new buildings are 
resistant to earthquakes and the fires temblors often cause and 13 
million people took part in the last national disasterprevention 
drill in september 
japan is a world leader in earthquake engineering newer 
buildings are designed not to collapse even in a quake registering 
about 8 on the richter scale said shinsuke nakata a design code 
specialist in the construction ministry 
japanese and us codes follow different philosophies nakata 
said a tendency to rigid construction in japan while california 
emphasizes improved margin of deformability in building codes 
that are much more sophisticated 
after the california quake tuesday japanese experts went to the 
san francisco bay area to study why one structure collapsed and 
another stood what the soil conditions were and other aspects of 
the disaster 
if tokyos new skyscrapers perform as well as those in san 
francisco most of the damage will occur elsewhere 
some experts believe japan is doing some things wrong however 
and that the inevitable great quake will be more costly as a result 
a fundamental problem is the dense tokyo area megalopolis of 
close to 30 million people nearly onequarter of the national 
population the archipelago is in the worlds most active seismic 
zone a meeting place of four tectonic plates 
japan and the surrounding seabed experience about 10 percent of 
global earthquake action the government says and tokyo is on a 
particularly active site even by japanese standards 
although residents of the city feel several quakes a year of low 
to medium intensity experts say this is a quiet time 
since a strong quake nearby in 1929 tokyo has not experienced 
a single tremor with an intensity of 5 or more katsuhiko 
ishibashi a seismologist with the construction ministry wrote in 
1987 
on the japanese intensity scale he cited 5 is a very strong 
quake just below the disastrous level the great quake of sept 1 
1923 which caused 140000 deaths in tokyo and nearby yokohama was 
a 7 the top of that scale 
no direct conversion is possible between the japanese scale and 
the openended richter which was developed later but the 1923 
tokyo quake was estimated to have had a 79 richter reading the 
1906 san francisco earthquake was estimated at 83 
ishibashi and other japanese scientists have focused on a 
volcanic eruption in 1986 on oshima island 70 miles south of 
tokyo as evidence of deadly seismic activity on the way 
if history repeats itself the next focus would be odawara 40 
miles south of tokyo and after that a great earthquake is likely 
toward the end of this century in the heavily populated tokai 
region a bit farther south he wrote 
these quakes are also likely to inaugurate an extended period 
of frequent and destructive earthquakes directly under tokyo bay 
he said 
ishibashi said japan must decentralize away from tokyo and the 
kanto plain on which it sits he urged national leaders to find a 
way of freeing ourselves from tokyos magnetic pull and steering 
japan clear of tragedy 
his article in the monthly chuo koron monthly said it was folly 
to proceed with plans for tokyo that put strong emphasis on 
building artificial islands in the bay to house several million 
people 
because of a phenomenon called liquefaction landfill can turn 
into something like quicksand in a big earthquake magnifying 
ground motion and damage he wrote even if buildings bridges 
and highways themselves are of earthquakeresistant or 
vibrationfree design 
some of the worst damage in san francisco this week was in the 
marina district built on landfill 
after the san francisco quake japanese tv viewers saw long 
programs on disaster measures at home often including maps of 
tokyo showing large areas already built on landfill and prone to 
liquefaction 
last year city authorities calculated the loss if tokyo were 
hit by a quake as strong as the 1923 disaster especially on a 
winter evening when cooking stoves and gas heaters were in use 
the estimate was 37000 dead 78000 injured onethird of homes 
and offices destroyed and massive disruption to communications and 
power supplies 
a study by the national land agency put the toll much higher 
150000 dead and 200000 injured 
tokai bank of nagoya calculated such a quake would cause damage 
valued at 570 billion or about 20 percent of japans economic 
output 
it predicted the flow of capital to the united states would be 
cut in half causing us interest rates to rise and stock markets 
to plunge worsening third world debt problems and threatening a 
world depression 
some japanese are fatalistic about the impending disaster one 
survey showed 94 percent of businesses thought they needed backup 
computer systems but only 95 percent had them 
you cant do anything about it a foreign ministry official 
said que sera sera 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

