<TEXT>
dozens of problems noted by inspectors 
of an oakland freeway over the years gave no hint of its disastrous 
collapse during a major earthquake a top california transportation 
official contends 
the periodic maintenance and repair reports described a sagging 
deck cracks flaking concrete bent spans a cracked girder and 
other problems since the cypress viaduct opened in 1957 
but the reports on the doubledeck nimitz freeway section that 
collapsed and crushed dozens of drivers were no cause for 
alarm caltrans chief engineer bill schaefer said friday the 
maintenance reports are not unusual at all 
caltrans structures chief jim roberts made similar remarks at a 
news conference saying i dont think its fraught with any more 
problemsbridges grow old like we do 
i wouldnt leave that thing open if i thought it was unsafe 
said roberts who was driving on the interstate 880 section the day 
before its top deck crashed onto the bottom deck 
roberts also insisted it was a lack of technology and not a lack 
of money that led to delays in earthquake safety improvements on 
i880 and similar elevated roads supported by outrigger columns 
on either side 
he also said the collapse of the freeway and the damage to two 
other twotiered roads in san francisco doesnt mean caltrans 
should stop building such structures he said use of new technology 
can ensure safety 
the three i880 the embarcadero and i280 were the only 
doubledeck freeways in northern california and all were closed by 
the quake 
roberts also said its not the caltrans policy to make easy 
repairs first to quakethreatened roads adding the worst case 
is being fixed first and he repeated that the 1milelong 
section of freeway that collapsed had not been viewed as a hazard 
caltrans has spent 54 million on firststage earthquake safety 
improvements mainly to tie roadways to support columns and is 
spending an additional 64 million on secondstage improvements to 
strengthen vertical columns but the plan doesnt include the 
nimitz freeway or other multicolumned freeways because they 
were considered safe 
roberts said the thirdstage work which involves strengthening 
doublecolumn supports will have to include roads such as the 
nimitz he said the thirdphase cost could run as high as 300 
million and research under way on how to fix doublecolumn 
structures will be speeded up 
he added that the cost of replacing the nimitz freeway section 
could range from 50 million to 100 million once its demolished 
schaefer and roberts also questioned various statements from 
outside engineers who have said i880 had an outdated design and 
was vulnerable to quakes 
you can talk to 100 engineers and get 100 different answers 
said schaefer roberts added we can armchair quarterback 
everything we do lets face it 
asked whether the fill land beneath the nimitz was too soft 
roberts said i dont think you can say the land is so unstable 
you cant build a bridge there reports made available friday by 
caltrans showed top layers of fill and rubble over soft clay and 
gravel 
another report produced in 1982 by the state department of 
mines and geology said in part the elevated section through 
downtown oakland is expected to be extensively damaged 
liquefaction and related ground failures will occur in a quake 
with a magnitude of 83 on the richter scale of ground motion 
tuesdays earthquake registered at 69 
the hydraulic fills used to construct miles of freeway along 
the east shore of san francisco bay in alameda county may liquefy 
during heavy shaking with long sections becoming totally 
impassable said the report to the governors emergency task 
force on earthquake preparedness 
of course the soils had a lot to do with the collapse said 
john kariotis one of the engineers offering criticism friday go 
back and look at pictures of oakland in 1916 it was all marsh that 
was filled in 
