four former cordis corp officials accused of 
selling defective heart pacemakers from 1983 to 1985 have been 
found innocent in federal court 
the defendants were acquitted friday after a sixweek trial on 
conspiracy and related charges in what the government claimed was 
the sale of 2200 defective pacemakers and 6000 corrosionprone 
batteries 
harold hershenson 62 a former executive vice president john 
pagones 64 former vice president for corporate product assurance 
stephen vadas 48 manager for product administration and dean 
ciporkin 42 senior reliability assurance engineer all were 
cleared by the 12member federal jury 
all four left cordis which has since sold off its pacemaker 
division 
the miamibased company itself previously had pleaded guilty and 
paid a 764000 fine along with 5 million in civil penalties to 
various federal agencies 
the fda said the pacemakers could have stopped without warning 
yet no deaths were attributed to failure of the devices implanted 
under the skin to regulate the heartbeat 
company officials knew of the problems but sold the pacemakers 
anyway according to the charges 
