a leader during the coal strikes that crippled the 
mining industry over the summer has been found dead and fellow 
miners fear he was the victim of a revenge killing a newspaper 
said saturday 
the body of alexander sotnikov a member of the regional strike 
committee in the donetsk coal basin in the ukraine was found last 
week in the village of zverevo the newspaper socialist industry 
reported 
it gave no details on the condition of the body or where exactly 
it was discovered sotnikovs age was not known 
the miners are seriously anxious the newspaper said 
could this be some kind of revenge on their comrade 
much of the soviet coal industry was paralyzed during the summer 
when hundreds of thousands of miners walked off the job to press 
for better working conditions and political changes 
instead of cracking down on the miners as it once would have 
the soviet government negotiated with them and conceded on many of 
their demands 
socialist industry said police were not prepared to say whether 
sotnikovs death was a result of foul play but a colleague said in 
a telephone interview that the strike leader was brutally 
murdered with his skull cracked by a blunt object and his face 
cut 
the colleague yuri boldyrev who also helped organize strikes 
said sotnikov had received threats telling him to stop trying to 
uncover corruption at the mine where he worked 
boldyrev did not say who he thought might be responsible he 
said sotnikov had three children ages five 10 and 17 
the minister of internal affairs vadim v bakatin is 
personally overseeing the investigation into sotnikovs death 
socialist industry said 
