<TEXT>
two months after noncommunists took over 
the government top officials are flashing solidarity 
vforvictory signs there is talk of developing a market 
economy and the new labor minister is on tv telling people prices 
have to go up 
there is a new mood and style in prime minister tadeusz 
mazowieckis administration the first noncommunist government in 
an east bloc country there is a clear effort in the premiers 
words to separate ourselves from the past with a thick line 
take juliusz burski new chairman of the state film committee 
he sits in a cavernous office in the ministry of culture the first 
time a director not a politician has the job 
he wants to give up the right to veto film projects sell the 
stateowned movie houses and create conditions to allow private 
filmmakers to blossom alongside the stateowned companies 
in my opinion the film industry should not be managed but 
should be allowed to live he said 
he ended the interview by explaining that there are no longer 
any banned films in poland and gave solidaritys trademark 
vforvictory sign 
across town at the ministry of building and spatial planning 
minister aleksander paszynski talks about the huge bureaucracy and 
his plans to solve a housing crisis that can force young couples to 
wait 15 to 20 years for an apartment 
his solution is to create postwar polands first free housing 
market he says he is studying the privatization of 
governmentowned apartments in prime minister margaret thatchers 
britain 
paszynski sees change in government working habits you have 
to work overtime or maybe even harder because the premier is 
after us he joked 
mazowiecki a journalist and former political prisoner came to 
power aug 24 through a stunning political manuever engineered by 
solidarity leader lech walesa who lured the communist partys 
former allies the peasants and democrats into a parliamentary 
coalition 
on sept 12 parliament approved a 24member cabinet that 
includes 12 members of solidarity there are just four communists 
heading foreign trade and the defense interior and transportation 
ministries one independent four peasants and three democrats make 
up the balance 
but the communist party remains a power to be reckoned with and 
wojciech jaruzelski the former communist party chief retains the 
powerful presidency 
most of the ministers are new to administration because 
executive jobs once were virtually off limits to anyone but 
communist party members the new cabinet is dominated by 
journalists professors and that vague designation in the east 
bloc political activist 
the confusion is less than you might have expected which does 
not mean that it is going smoothly paszynski said 
in virtually every ministry there are signs of radical change 
justice minister aleksander bentkowski asked victims of 
stalinist crimes to come forward so their cases can be investigated 
interior minister czeslaw kiszczak dissolved the muchhated zomo 
riot police 
minister of education henryk samsonowicz receives members of the 
oncebanned independent students association 
foreign minister krzysztof skubiszewski argues against deporting 
back to east germany refugees reaching poland 
labor minister jacek kuron a born rabblerouser and thorn in 
the side of every communist leader of the last three decades has 
appeared on television in a denim shirt and chainsmoking american 
cigarettes to explain why prices must go up 
despite such symbolic acts there have been some complaints 
principally surrounding television and information policy 
mazowiecki made clear he wanted no witch hunts meaning the 
old ranks could keep their jobs as long as they loyally followed 
instructions of the new ministers and displayed competence 
mazowieckis appointee to head the radiotelevision committee 
controlling state broadcasting andrzej drawicz fired no one he 
did reassign to offcamera jobs three newscasters who were most 
associated with the martiallaw propaganda of the early 1980s 
the communist party daily trybuna ludu protested loudly 
comparing it to the 198283 purge of hundreds of prosolidarity 
journalists 
there were also complaints from solidarity that more people 
should have disappeared from television screens and that the style 
of presenting news still gives disproportionate attention to the 
communist party 
another complaint voiced by walesa among others is that the 
new government is not doing enough to explain its economic policies 
at a time when prices are leaping by 50 percent a month 
mazowiecki wants to undo the old centralized economy in one to 
two years and has been willing to take on entrenched interests 
within the communist party and among his own followers 
solidaritys rankandfile suffered when the government 
persuaded parliament to limit automatic costofliving increases to 
help plug the budget gap and fight inflation 
another sacred cow the coal industry is about to feel the 
sting as the government reduces subsidies by the equivalent of 571 
million in coming weeks some inefficient mines may have to close 
deputy prime minister leszek balcerowicz hopes to sign an imf 
standby loan agreement next month something previous communist 
governments were unable to negotiate in 3 years 
the sharp turn to a market economy foresees heightened inflation 
at first as price controls end and state subsidies that lowered 
prices are eliminated price increases have accelerated under 
mazowiecki a loaf of bread that cost 11 cents a year ago is now 27 
cents and quart of milk that cost about 5 cents now costs about 45 
cents 
but the price increases far greater than those that toppled 
communist governments in the past are so far accepted with pained 
understanding by consumers strikes have gradually died out 
that reflects the popularity of the mazowiecki government 
how long the initial trust will last is anybodys guess but one 
prosolidarity teacher said the world might be surprised at poles 
patience now that they have a government they support 
</TEXT>
