<DOCNO> AP891021-0091 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
warsaw poland the communistlinked trade union alliance on 
saturday urged a limited nationwide protest to oppose price hikes 
and plans to privatize stateowned property but it stopped short 
of calling for work stoppages 
union members are to hang banners and posters at their 
workplaces and office buildings from monday to friday the opzz 
alliance said in a statement published in weekend newspapers 
in declaring the protest opzz cited factors such as prices 
going up madly speculation selling out the national property and 
the phantom of hunger and poverty for many polish families 
it said no work stoppages were called thanks only to a promise 
by deputy prime minister leszek balcerowicz that he would take 
opzzs concerns under consideration 
opzz said current economic reform plans would halt pay increases 
at a time when prices are rising uncontrollably this it said 
would bring growing poverty and the possibility of a social 
outburst 
the alliance also said not enough is being done to increase the 
flow of goods to the market and that the economic program as 
formulated would lead to higher inflation 
government plans call for reducing subsidies to factories 
expected to cause higher prices initially and reducing wage 
increases in an attempt to balance the state budget and introduce a 
tight money policy the government hopes that policy eventually 
will bring inflation under control 
some state property such as factories is to be sold off the 
government says the process will be gradual marked by competitve 
bidding and will take different forms such as public stock sales 
foreign investments or employee buyouts 
the government has warned poles to expect difficult times 
including bankruptcies and unemployment but says the situation 
should stabilize by the end of next year 
opzz has called for talks between workers and the government to 
win public support for the economic reforms and the communist 
party supports the idea 
we note with concern that a number of important decisions 
undertaken or planned by the government are not consulted with 
social groups or their concerned representatives said a 
statement by party spokesman jan bisztyga last week 
such important concepts cannot be implemented without 
social approval without the consent of the working people and an 
agreement signed by them he said 
he said the changes require an accord such as the one reached in 
april after talks between the government and opposition those 
talks led to elections that resulted in solidarity taking over the 
government 
opzz created by communist authorities in 1982 to try to 
supplant solidarity has always been considered by solidarity a 
hollow shell supported only by communist activists and careerists 
in factories 
it has been struggling in recent years to establish credibility 
as a real union and often takes more militant stances than 
solidarity 
although opzz unions claim 6 million members about three times 
as many as solidarity an opzz picketing action outside parliament 
oct 13 that was to draw representatives from around the country 
attracted only about 150 people 
opzz says solidarity and the solidarityled government of prime 
minister tadeusz mazowiecki are committed to reintroducing 
capitalis in poland it portrays itself as the defender of the 
common worker and socialist social values such as protecting the 
needy 
the deeply divided communist party a participant in the 
government has so far gone along with mazowieckis plans and 
offered only muted criticism 
</TEXT>
