<TEXT>
from the pursuit of democracy to 
an unbending adherence to socialism communist countries are 
responding in vastly different ways to the reforms of soviet leader 
mikhail s gorbachev 
the power shift in east germany last week was another reminder 
of the influence of reform movements rippling across the east bloc 
but the speed and the scope of change varies depending on the 
level of tolerance at the top 
poland is pursuing democracy and a free market economy with a 
vigor borne of economic desperation romania though also plagued 
with terrible food shortages and skyrocketing inflation is keeping 
a tight grip on socialism 
czechoslovakia and hungary are in somewhat better shape 
economically but czechoslovakia jails prodemocracy dissenters 
while hungary says they can run for political office next year 
seemingly adrift in this unpredictable ideological sea is east 
germany long considered a hardline adherent to communism but now 
something of a question mark 
communist party officials in east germany acted to remove erich 
honecker as leader only after mounting protests at home and a flood 
of emigrants to the west deeply embarrassed the orthodox socialist 
leadership 
the new leader 52yearold egon krenz has been considered a 
hardliner also but he tried to give the impression of 
conciliation during his first days in office and on saturday he 
was quoted as saying there may be important lessons to be 
learned from gorbachevs reforms 
the man who gave strength to the communist reform movement 
gorbachev continues to lead the soviet union down a rocky path of 
greater openness and a less centralized economy 
gorbachev who must deal with sniping from the right and the 
left over his policies and a phalanx of ethnic disputes in the 
soviet republics has said he will not interfere in what the rest 
of the warsaw pact alliance is doing 
moscow however is expected to keep siding with east germany 
czechoslovakia and other eastern european countries that hold the 
partys leading role sacrosanct 
in east germany the new forum and other opposition groups used 
gorbachevs visit to the country earlier this month to press for 
reform 
if gorbachev werent there the new forum people would be sent 
to the hinterlands or be sitting in prison says eastwest expert 
josef janning of the university of mainz 
western countries have made it clear they are willing to help 
those countries undertaking political and economic reforms the 
us house overwhelmingly approved 837 million in aid to poland 
and hungary on thursday nearly double what the white house had 
asked 
only the market place only free enterprise can solve the 
desperate economic problems of the eastern countries us 
secretary of commerce robert a mosbacher said in a speech in 
frankfurt last week 
marxist economics do not work 
despite that assertion there are likely to be problems ahead as 
growing calls for capitalistoriented free enterprise clash with 
the cradletograve socialism that now reigns in eastern europe 
the changes have created much friction between hardline and 
progressive countries hungary infuriated warsaw pact ally east 
germany in september by opening its western borders to east german 
refugees 
that was only one of several changes initiated by the 
reformminded leaders in budapest who also have promoted greater 
free enterprise and promised free elections by june 
this free elections characterizes all modern democratic 
legal states interior minister istvan horvath told parliament on 
thursday 
although the leadership has disbanded the communist party in a 
symbolic move the top figures remain at the head of the newly 
created socialist party 
poland is giddy over becoming the first east bloc country led by 
noncommunists but is facing the potential for more unrest as it 
implements tough austerity measures 
communists meanwhile still control the foreign trade defense 
interior and transportation ministries 
bulgaria has been paying lip service to reform and has 
introduced limited economic changes but is unlikely to change much 
under 78yearold leader todor zhivkov 
in czechoslovakia the communist government responded to a wave 
of prodemocracy protests in january with carefully targeted 
repression of key activists 
that prompted czechoslovak playwright and human rights activist 
vaclav havel who was jailed for four months this year to speak of 
a country where one is still thrown in jail for his words and 
where socialism has become a rubber truncheon 
in romania the east bloc reform movement irked stalinist 
president nicolae ceausescu so much that he suggested warsaw pact 
intervention to block solidaritys takeover in poland 
ceausescus ironfisted 24year rule in romania refuses to 
budge despite chronic shortages of food and fuel that leave 
thousands literally shivering in their homes each winter 
yugoslavia though not a member of the soviet bloc has been 
grappling with serious ethnic clashes that until now have 
overshadowed growing calls to banish the communist partys power 
monopoly 
yugoslavs for decades have enjoyed the freedoms that many of 
their eastern european neighbors would cherish the country faces 
mounting economic troubles and an inflation rate of nearly 1200 
percent while hundreds of thousands have gone to the west in 
search of work 
