<TEXT>
president bush on saturday signed a 9 million 
aid package designed to help the political opposition running 
against nicaraguas ruling sandinista government in next years 
election 
the money to be spent for general political activity such as 
registering voters and getting them to the polls is to start 
flowing into the central american country in the next 10 days to be 
used during the voter registration period that concludes at the end 
of october 
the stated purpose of the aid package which congress sent to 
bush on friday is to level the playing field for the underfinanced 
opposition the money is to go to registering nicaraguans 
including thousands who have left their homeland and paying for 
poll monitoring vote counting and other electionrelated 
activities 
however because of nicaraguan regulation of foreign 
contributions some of the money as much as 2 million probably 
will end up with the sandinistacontrolled national election 
council 
critics allege the package is merely an attempt by the united 
states to buy out the sandinistas through political influence after 
years of failure to oust them by militarily backing the contra 
rebels 
but white house press secretary marlin fitzwater said in a 
statement that the step reflects administration hopes that through 
fair elections nicaragua will join other countries that have made 
the transition from repression to freedom 
the aid which passed congress easily represents another step 
forward in our efforts to promote democracy in countries that have 
been deprived of political and economic freedom fitzwaters 
statement said around the world the tide of democracy is 
advancing as more and more authoritarian and totalitarian regimes 
realize that human progress is inseparable from the principles of 
liberty 
bushs action comes just before his twoday trip to costa rica 
for a hemispheric democracy celebration where nicaraguas president 
daniel ortega also will attend along with many heads of state from 
the western hemisphere 
they are to participate on friday and saturday in a centennial 
celebration of costa rican democracy hosted by that nations 
president oscar arias 
bush earlier acknowledged in a letter to lawmakers that because 
of the nicaraguan election laws as much as 2 million of the 
package would have to go to the sandinistacontrolled supreme 
electoral council but he said that situation should not be used 
as a transparent attempt to prevent the united states from helping 
its democratic friends 
under nicaraguan rules on foreign money donated to the electoral 
process 50 percent of the money spent in certain categories must 
go the supreme electoral council the council oversees and 
regulates the election process 
most of the us aid is to go through the national endowment for 
democracy a quasigovernmental agency that promotes democratic 
elections around the world to pay for ostensibly nonpartisan 
activities like voter registration election monitoring and party 
building 
part of the money also will go to independent groups that will 
monitor the feb 25 elections including one headed by former 
president carter 
the legislation was vague on how the money will be used but 
congressional observers said it appeared that up to 6 million 
could go directly to the national opposition union a coalition 
group that is backing the presidential candidacy of opposition 
newspaper publisher violeta chamorro 
however money is not to go directly into her campaign coffers 
or be used for advertising to promote her candidacy backers say 
the national endowments charter forbids such partisan campaign 
activity but administration officials believe that spending money 
on the democratic process will ultimately benefit mrs chamorro 
who is at a heavy financial disadvantage to the pervasive 
sandinista party 
bush in his letter lobbying congress to pass the package said 
mrs chamorros party needs our assistance desperately 
with the funds provided for in this legislation the national 
endowment for democracy and other organizations will work to 
strengthen democratic institutions in nicaragua so that truly free 
and fair elections may be held fitzwater said saturday 
the 9 million is money reprogrammed from the state departments 
agency for international development 
an administration official said 5 million will go to ned to be 
dispensed to mrs chamorros group while the other 4 million will 
go to election monitoring groups and to the supreme electoral 
council to match money for unos activities that fall under the 50 
percent rule 
</TEXT>
