<TEXT>
a navstar navigation satellite 
rocketed into orbit saturday to join a network of spacecraft that 
guide bombers warships missiles and ground troops with pinpoint 
accuracy 
an air force delta 2 rocket propelled the 65 million satellite 
into an orbit ranging out to 11000 miles high following a fiery 
liftoff that brilliantly illuminated the predawn sky 
the satellite has been picked up we sent commands and its 
responding as expected said air force col marty runkle the 
mission director it appeared to be a normal mission he said 
information on rocket performance was delayed nearly an hour 
because a tracking station on ascension island in the south 
atlantic also was supporting the space shuttle atlantis at the 
time trackers there recorded the rocket data and later played it 
back to the launch control center here 
the navstar is the fourth in a new series of spacecraft that 
enable us and allied military units such as planes ships 
submarines tanks and field troops to precisely determine their 
positions to within 50 feet in any type of weather anywhere in the 
world 
they tune in on the networks radio signals using receivers as 
small as a handheld telephone 
the satellites also keep track of the speed of military units 
within a fraction of a mile per hour and the precise time within a 
millionth of a second 
</TEXT>
