<TEXT>
buck alvin helm a beefy longshoreman who 
splits his time between the oakland waterfront and the klamath 
mountains is strong tough and ornery those traits served him 
well in a deathdefying 90hour ordeal on a crumpled highway 
helms family and friends know him as an occasionally 
cantankerous familyloving man with a booming voice who knows how 
to survive and survive he did through three nights of terrifying 
conditions inside his crushed car in the concrete wreckage of the 
nimitz freeway 
asked what kept his father alive so long greg helm responded 
hes an ornery old fart 
helm 57 has worked in the bay area since 1969 as a shipping 
clerk for local 34 of the international longshoremens and 
warehousemens union a former teacher he has worked most recently 
at the port of oakland keeping track of the cargo received and 
delivered on the waterfront 
most weekends and sometimes on weekdays he drives 250 miles 
north to weaverville on the edge of the klamath mountains to visit 
his children and his exwife with whom he remains good friends 
his silver chevrolet sprint mashed in the wreckage had nearly 
200000 miles on it 
news of his miraculous survival and rescue shot through the town 
of 3500 like a lightning bolt saturday 
one woman came into tops market where buck shops the largest 
grocery store in town and hollered at the top of her lungs they 
found him they found him according to assistant manager tony 
giassullo 
a group of helms friends and relatives was watching television 
together at the home of his exwife lorene when news came that he 
was alive 
everyone was happy yelling crying and holding each other 
said frank desmond a friend of helms son jeff mrs helm was 
saying thank god 
said former nexttodoor neighbor cathy hardisty i still got 
chills all over my body at him living through that 
helms tale of survival starts with his own misfortune in timing 
after finishing up work at 5 pm helm and basil parker a 
coworker for the last six years left the howard terminal and 
headed north on the nimitz parker for his home in berkeley and 
helm for weaverville seconds after passing helm and waving to him 
parker looked in his rearview mirror as the earthquake struck 
helm who had been about 10 car lengths behind him was gone 
right now all i can say is im glad to see him alive said 
parker im happy for his family more than anything 
helm described by one acquaintance as about 6 feet tall 240 
pounds and pretty goodsized around the middle is a wellknown 
figure in weaverville his family has lived there about 10 years 
