almost every weekend at the nugget restaurant 
hes big strong tough and ornery she said im not 
surprised he survived he always comes in here with all his kids 
and their friends hes a real good dad im ecstatic hes alive 
so is weaverville resident fred meyer who described his friend 
as a big bear of a guy 
he has a booming voice and a heart of gold meyer said 
 
peggy mcconnell of weaverville said helm is one of her best 
friends she said he stands out as an individualist in this 
fundamentalist redneck little town 
mcconnell 40 described helms car as dirty and disorganized 
and said it might have contained food and water she said he had 
access to a van that he slept in while in the bay area in order to 
save money even though he makes plenty of money 
 
the day after the 69 quake helms former wife walked into 
weaverville variety office supply in a daze and spoke with store 
owner pat zugg 
she said she had a gut feeling that he was trapped in that 
freeway she said she was pretty stunned he hadnt called to 
say he was ok so she knew something wasnt right he was very 
familyoriented every time i saw him he was with his kids 
helms coworkers on the waterfront had known for days that he 
was almost surely among the victims on the devastated stretch of 
freeway when radio and television reported he had been found many 
called in to the local 34 office to share the good news 
were all ecstatic said dave comport a shipping 
superintendent who works in the same terminal as helm we figured 
that if anybody could make it buck helm could hes tough hes a 
fighter 
frances lona secretary for the local 34 main office in san 
francisco characterized helm and his coworkers as wild 
characters but said he is a great guy 
hes now a guy with a new nickname according to coworker bob 
bombarde 
were going to call him lucky bucky from now on bombarde 
said 
